Title: The Drunkard: A Novel by Liu Yichang (Hong Kong Literature)
Author: Yichang Liu

Title: Desert Plants: Conversations With 23 American Musicians
Author: Walter Zimmermann
My Review: This collection of interviews rambles a bit, where a more conventional book might put context and prefer concise sketches of these composers in question - but, in my opinion, this collection works because it allows these composers and free-thinkers to elaborate, on their own terms, the conditions and qualifications of their work in such a way that defy easy categorization. Even the ridiculous money-scrounging episode of La Monte Young's was contributed with permission - as is the wealth of excerpted scores and letters reprinted here. This is a true wealth and document of its times, and any aspiring artist/composer/figure fascinated by the avant-garde collective in America (and Toronto!) will find this essential reading.

Title: Sculpting in Time
Author: Andrei Tarkovsky
My Review:
This is a wonderful distillation of impulse-methodology that Tarkovsky has gifted us, and one replete with anecdotes on his own creative choices; his primer, because it is so wide-encompassing, can stretch further beyond the craft of filmmaking, but is first and foremost dedicated thoroughly to its construction as a summation of the being.

I also hate how this edition has been formatted, unfortunately - it's hard to distinguish without reading original copies, but the insertion of Arseny Tarkovsky's poems in tandem with Andrey's observations, in the presentation here, interrupt the latter by their inclusion in the middle of a sentence, rather than act as complementary to the artistry provided (as I suspect was intended).

What ensues is a cacophony of text and image that serve to distract and impede the observations Andrey held to their absolute zenith.

Title: Poems: Book One of Our Trakl
Author: Georg Trakl
My Review:
Sing a song of spiders wrinkled
with lepers yelp blue bruised skin hues
and a touch of fruit stained partly sunny
now o! - a chance of God's absence

the rot had not yet set in, the hope still faint.
He gives and gives now to his successors,
and his mud stained voice remains.

Title: The Limits of Fabrication: Materials Science, Materialist Poetics
Author: Nathan Brown
My Review: A genuinely exemplary examination of objectivism vs objectism, with an exploration of Christian Bök and Caroline Bergvall, to deconstruction of poetics through scientific language in Shanxing Wang's "Mad Science in Imperial City." My reading made it hard to understand the language and logic in the first two sections of this book, but overall it was extremely investing.

Title: The Art of Being: Poetics of the Novel and Existentialist Philosophy
Author: Yi-Ping Ong
My Review: An extremely frustrating and elephantine summation of a large corpus of works, all situated within a Western canon - moreso incredible that Yi-Ping Ong can summate these works, but entirely more frustrating that her argumentative voice is stifled, muzzled, and ultimately submerged by the many quotations and narratives that she invokes in her stead. This book also feels like a precursor to a very engaging sort of undergraduate class, one that - with more time to digest the books in full - would amplify her argument on the poetics of the novel, but here becomes entirely secondary and merely epistolary when taken on its own.

Title: How the Days of Love and Diphtheria
Author: Robert Kloss
My Review:
Robert Kloss is a writer that merits larger distinction. His work is largely cerebral, and easy comparison invites Gothic claim to his enterprise; regardless, his writing is more Malick in nature than Cormac McCarthy's gruff work, though Kloss' only real competitor in style is perhaps Joseph McElroy.

I'm inviting a lot of praise in Kloss' writing thus far because it is so self-assured, and the premise rather black with intrigue, though truthfully this my yet be early in judgement.

Title: Antígona González

My Review:
The urgent manifesto detailing, as only irrupted fragmentation can, the vague lifelessness of a journey to find trace of the dead. A translation, with an understanding that translation can only approximate the intent of the author, which may in turn only approximate the intent of the many parsed and invoked texts, a necromancy whose voice is yet servicing the voicelessness of the erased.

The whiteness of silence. The whiteness of silence.

Author: Lucy Ellmann
My Review: Four seems a perfect amount - for the daunting length is  easily digestible by how fun the narrative loops, with each "narrative intermission" a less-ambulatory yet still thematically consonant to the main "one mammoth of a sentence" narrative. It is not always perfect in its asides and intermingling of the two narratives, but each is satisfying by themselves, and both are richer in their conjoinment.

Title: Raising Moths. Attempts at (Musical) Ekphrasis on Haruomi Hosono's Watering a Flower
Author: Federico Antonini
My Review:
A case where the Afterword really belongs as a preface to the entire body of work, and even then with a bit of a disclaimer. The body of work is composed of copyright free passages taken from the dennisnorthey upload of Watering a Flower, but by this nature the book is always at risk of being obsolete from newly amended and added comments after this publication.

More focus, too, could be spent discussing the paradoxical juxtaposition of digital permanence and the ephemeral nature of the music as picked up by the YouTube comments. A discourse on Neverland-esque Lost Boys mentality aside, there is also a striking lack of discussion in turn on the ideation presented within YT, and certain contextual anecdotes would be well-served for comments (memetic material and references to 4chan, for example, as a way of expanding the cultural diaspora presented here).

Title: Ghosts Are Just Strangers Who Know How to Knock
Author: Hillary  Leftwich
My Review:
The opening few stories read a bit uneven in my perspective, seemingly attached more by narrative novelty (the mundane observation tethered by a personal twist) than any recognizable stylistic impetus, but this does change rather quickly. The longer, more narrative-driven entries engage the reader best, as they unfold both mundane and surrealist qualities in a way that complement and in fact emerge from the other.

This might be a re-read in the future (Amazon delivered a damaged book as a new sale, so here's to a return where a proper new copy is sent).

Title: The Disconnected
Author: Oğuz Atay
My Review:
It owns and is worth grabbing if you can find it (which seems to be a rare thing).
Nothing I can add which hasn't already been expounded upon by others (see: Nathan Gaddis), so all I'll say is that it's a triumph of translation that sorely needs to be reissued for the general public.

Title: The Collected Poems
Author: Larry Eigner
My Review: A staggering monolith of a collection easily boasting 1800+ pages, these poems will easily tire you out with the confined perspectives they offer - which is, arguably, the point, or much of it. I cannot understand for the life of me why the set is structured the way it is, however - the appendices really give further insight into the composition of Eigner's poems, in a way that the brief comments by the editor precluding each section absolutely do not. It's also a mammoth undertaking to read, so proceed with caution (maybe start with a sampling).

Title: Sundog
Author: Scott       Walker
My Review:
A selective and well-represented curation of lyrics with thoughtful presentation, linking Walker in ways to poets like David UU and J.H. Prynne. It's hard to reckon that this book might well be considered the last testament to Scott Walker's legacy, considering thr Six Songs at the end (which suggest a ripe musicality that is now forever a promise impossible to reach).

It's also purely fun to see the same context supplied in the album liner notes reproduced here, as - in the guise of a book of poetry - there is added meaning, though not one easily supplied. It's well worth the hunt.

Title: Stockhausen Serves Imperialism
Author: Cornelius Cardew
My Review: Concise if lopsided criticism levied against (of course) Stockhausen, Cage, and later himself. If the content is a bit sparing, it does demonstrate a fierce acuity of political thought intersected within musical grounds, even if the latter is not fully expounded on.

Title: press start to translate: This is what happens when you let a computer translate a video game?
Author: Clyde Mandelin
My Review:
Really more of a 3.5, but I'm fluctuating between giving this an out and out four stars because of the way the content is presented - though, at the same time, it's definitely done in a manner that demonstrates the topic at hand.

There is a lot of content to wade through here! Clyde Mandelin does an expert job of going through the thought process of the Google Translate algorithm / neural network, with some hypothesizing along the way to demonstrate how machine translations can interpret sentences and ideas that we, with context-enriched understanding, take for granted. Some of the content is a little too repetitive for my liking and could have been summarized a bit better in the final thoughts section, and the main comparative captures do feel like appendices rather than main content, but overall it's a wholly legible (if exhausting) demonstration of how and why machine translation isn't (yet) reliable, even 3 years from the original publication.

Title: The Devil’s Dictionary
Author: Ambrose Bierce
My Review:
The one dictionary that deserves to be read as well as parsed through for individual content. Unfortunately, as eager and intelligent its inventions against human callousness, there are qualities (look no further than sections M and N, for example) that draw it back from being a thoroughly composed master stroke.

It is essential reading, both as cadaver of that so called wit, and as a document for how far human progress has come since - and, of course, how cogent it still is in its depiction.

Title: The Last Temptation of Bond
Author: Kimmy Beach
My Review:
Really, it’s going to be a toss-up; from what I can tell, the author wanted to explore the commercial and populist aspects of the character, and has in-depth knowledge on the series to particularly dissect the Bond franchise - because this is no eulogy of any sort.

Then again, this approach to Bond (through modernist literature) only highlights how markedly removed and escapist the Bond franchise has become, to the point where addressing each totemic incarnation is moot, and the final sequence can’t quite come to grips with rendering a Bond-like caricature human or mundane in the end.

Props for the work, though, but the reader is going to have to make a decision on whether this works for themselves.

Title: Who Censored Roger Rabbit? (Roger Rabbit, #1)
Author: Gary K. Wolf
My Review:
Ridiculous and sublime qualities all lined up in a pastiche of detective and cartoon tropes. Legitimate criticism has been outlined already by this - you wouldn’t guess the ending without cheating a bit - and of course, this would be consumed by its vastly more successful incarnation, Who Framed Roger Rabbit.

But for all its shortcomings, one persistent quality shines through, and that’s the earnestness of a bugger who’s managed to mesh together childhood influences into something that teeters on the edge of rhapsodic nostalgia. The Centipede Press edition is a short, small thing, and the author’s note doesn’t quite go into detail in the way the reader might care for, but it’s evident that care and pride went into this novel, and it’s definitely worth a check out.

Just, you know, don’t get hung up on the excessive purple prose. Both the novel and the movie place the emphasis on the inherent melancholy of cartoons over the saturated societal faults of detective fiction.

Title: Philippe Grandrieux: Sonic Cinema (EX:CENTRICS)
Author: Greg Hainge
My Review:
It’s great to see a book on Philippe Grandrieux and even more so to see someone clearly passionate on his works, but it is unfortunately undermined by the need to describe the happenstance of his films - understandable given their scarcity on home video (and other formats). More frustrating, too, is the early writing’s admission on not being quite as eloquent as others, which ends up undermining his relationship with the audience/reader in terms of scrutinization.

It is an honest effort and one that is readily welcomed; slight editing and restructuring (such as the use of “sonic cinema” and its explanation) could help bolster the argument some. The real fruit, hopefully, is exposing cinéastes and film theorists alike to Grandrieux’s works.

Title: A Naked Singularity
Author: Sergio de la Pava
My Review:
After a long gestation, it is done. This printing could have used a bit of proof-correction for some incidental things (and I don’t mean in terms of stylistic transgressions, but actual “you’re” placed instead of “your” kind of errors).

The opening and closing redeemed a rather turgid part 2, but the cover blurb contains beats that the reader should rather discover on their own. Good all around.

Title: The Leftovers
Author: Tom Perrotta
My Review:
The worst thing you can do to a concept is to divorce it from the fantastic, because inevitably you’ll try to drown out the barren ideas with descriptors meant to provide characterization.

There are some good comedic moments, to be fair, and the last chapter has a good sense of momentum to it that furthers a look at an internal dissolution, rather than external detritus. But it does say something that the TV series — even the first season — is more engaging, and not because there is more violence in it.

Title: Art and Lies
Author: Jeanette Winterson
My Review: Might be more of a 3.5, not sure - Winterson’s writing is (as expected) masterfully crafted, but here the personages are not so much fully fleshed out as they are figures simply wearing names, and in writing their articulations are indistinguishable from one another. So be it for a work that strives for counterpoint, but writing does not necessarily get a pass because of its conceit; it must also execute it superbly.

Title: Oh, My Sweet Alien! Omnibus (Oh, My Sweet Alien!, #1-2)
Author: Kouji Miyata
My Review:
what a weird book to add to the collection

pros:
- it’s genuinely sweet and slice-of-life
- ample context is given to character actions
- well-drawn

cons:
- art is sometimes too cluttered for my tastes
- wish-fulfilment fantasy (take that as you will)
- pacing seems rather abrupt; the reader gets the sense the author ran out of ideas to explore
- world-building is minimal, characters themselves are boring without any chance to grow

it’s disingenuous to really “critique” a slim volume here since it explores tropes and ideas common to this kind of material. then again, I did read it, so there must be some sort of pull to this material?

Title: Leap-Seconds
Author: Paul Zits
My Review:
At its best, Leap-Seconds offers a glimmer of that "language of violence" that its blurb maintains is the core focus of the work, but too often its fragmentary narrative seems woefully designed as such; that the terse, single-minded repetition should come to dominate means that these "fragments" here become indistinguishable from the others, and designed to neatly (or intentionally) pair. It makes for relatively smooth reading (as much as smooth can be when dealing with specific interludes of children's interjections), but as a result, everything inhabits a turgid, lifeless air about it. That doubles with small excerpts from other authors, whose snippets enlighten the reading and make a clear difference already in terms of diction.

(Might try to revisit one day, and not speed through it like some sort of demon; perhaps that reading might illuminate more for me than this cursory one did.)

Title: The Egg: Stories by Michael Gira
Author: Michael Gira
My Review:
There are thoughtful ruminations inside this slim volume.

The biggest strength and weakness, insofar as my experience with Gira’s writing goes, is his mannered tone in writing, his refusal to submit to throes of horror except when conjoined with absolute erotic exposure. Otherwise, his writing is thoroughly dry, and the stories inside more sketches and self-tuned variations on the same kind of “hatching” / oblivion that makes his live shows enthralling to watch.

Included with this volume is a CD.
I haven’t yet listened to it.

I would speculate that the best way to read this would be on a digital platform, with a wide enough display that you’d be able to set up two pages per screen refresh. I say this purely because the “bleed” from one page to another, ink-wise, distracted me a little from the work.

And what a disquieting tome of ideas!

Title: Tiny World
Author: Rebecca Woodmass
My Review:
This, the debut published work of Rebecca Woodmass (to my knowledge, anyhow), demands to burrow itself, lie at your side as you wake and sleep, take in with you the joys and storms of a day's journey. It yields its best treasures then, and the most singular treasure that I took from it was Woodmass' singular voice. It remains consistent and engaging throughout the entirety of this collection, and - to my delight - it is firm in resisting affectation.

At the same time, my preferences in poetry lie with the paring of words, and ultimately the layout of the copy I have in my hands. Since its initial release on Lulu Press, Inc., I know Woodmass has created a second edition, one which i think is a bit shorter in dimensions, and with a different cover. I'm not sure in what ways the poems may differ - if indeed they do - but I can imagine the spacing and layout will differ slightly. I mention this particularly because I do think Woodmass' words intend to be savoured, sometimes in slight breaking of pages and on their own merits. The copy I have does stagger a bit in terms of spacing (most notable in "A Return Home"), so I think my initial rating reflects that a bit here.

More so in this collection, the same redolent themes appear in different incarnations - perhaps to the point of excess. That may very well be the point, but it does nag at me briefly to see the same gesture (trees and roots as a comparative note towards one's self-growth and self-value; the value/reverse value of "Triggers") without a pause, or a new variation that allows to re-examine the conclusions in earlier works with a more pronounced light. Her writing, too, almost demands to both gulp down its content and to stay a breath's distance away, which might be more to do with how the material here is organized. Again, preference counts - you as the reader may find difference with me here, and that I think would be highly encouraged.

Regardless of all this errata I've typed here, I do think Rebecca Woodmass has cultivated a voice all her own - her Instagram presence, as well as her continued work in support of raising awareness, attest to that, and in triumphant strides of self-development. Coming soon, as she's teased on Instagram, is her second collection. I look forward, eagerly, to its arrival.

Title: Milk and Honey
Author: Rupi Kaur
My Review:
Edit: Thought about my reaction and changed my wording to better reflect my thoughts now.

—-

The thing about writing universally is that you shouldn’t be writing “universal truths,” but commanding a universal audience to touch the throes of your vision. Writing “raw” and pulped with emotion also runs the risk of saying absolutely nothing.

This book does a good job at letting the reader overlay their emotional reaction onto the words themselves, but - and perhaps tragically so - the poems themselves don’t amount to anything, independent of the reader who attributes themselves into these etchings.

What made Warsan Shire’s poetry work is a writing identity; that kind of identity that gives Shire’s work context (“this is the everyday,” one might intuit) and thus a sense of credibility. In Kaur’s collection, no such context exists: you’d have to read her foreword, included in an exclusive hardcover edition, to understand that she intended to write in lowercase as a nod, and as ode to Gurmukhi (“a script in which punjabi is written only uses the period,”(sic) notes Kaur). Does that translate well into the poems at hand? Not to my reading.

The failure of this work is a sum total of ambition and raw excess. It seems more clear to me that this is the work of someone who has experienced heartache of a massive kind, and has come out the better for it through writing. I won’t fault that - Kaur mentions she is already much different now than she was when she wrote milk and honey. But a published work is very different in evaluation from that of a personal journal, and the ideas here begin to attain shape more as personal mantra than an act of transformation.

Title: The Conference of the Birds
Author: Attar of Nishapur
My Review:
This is pertaining particularly to the Sholeh Wolpé translation.

I expect this is a particularly ravishing rendering of the Attah original. It’s a gorgeous English text, in the hands of Wolpé.

I’m slightly disappointed that there isn’t much in the way of contextualizing, or discussing this work in how it relates to Sufism and to its contributions toward literature edification - though this is likely an effort to realize The Conference on its own merits. There is a brief Introduction supplied by Sholeh Wolpé, which is nice to have, at least.

Completionists be wary: a footnote, at the end of this edition, mentions “[t]he prologue in this work is not part of the story ... Therefore, I have chosen to exclude it from this edition.” If that’s the kind of thing that precludes your purchase of a particular edition, you may want to steer away.

Title: Teaching My Mother How to Give Birth
Author: Warsan Shire
My Review:
Recommended to me by the clerk at Metrotown. A very passionate employee, with love for the way words burrow under the skin and ululate the most vivid nightmares.

This collection is more trauma than “poetry,” and I think this kind of poetic sub-genre (should I call it that?) demand to be read in full, rather than piecemeal. The effect, then, of this collection is rather to inform the reader of conditions as perceived by the wordsmith. It does a good job; words are pungent with meaning, and it’s quite impossible to trace any ambiguity with enough close reading.

Not really a book for the everyday, and truthfully I don’t think I’m the right audience for this, but if you want beauty and grief commingled together this is the book for you. It’s definitely worth the read.

Title: Ancient Evenings: A Novel
Author: Norman Mailer
My Review:
After so long a time in putting it off, the tale is now complete.

There's some exceptionally vivid writing here, some that I'm sure has been put to more consistent usage in Mailer's output - as this was my first encounter (don't do this, please), I can only guess as to his power in writing.

The scope of it, all gargantuan and fecund with shit and malady, is epic on the level of myth making, but - and here's the but - its scope sometimes is inconsistent with the very nature of its storytelling. The first few pages are remarkable, but the brunt of the tale is mired with description of so much offal that it becomes tiresome, and worse, tedious. Perhaps it speaks to our Age of Information that what used to be outrageous in print now seems like crude exercise to the blasphemy of online erotica?

In the end, reading through this piecemeal has helped to appreciate - and probably mystify - the book a bit better. I can imagine why Matthew Barney would find this material attractive, and it's material worth visiting, even if in the end it is too wildly varying in tone to recommend.

Author: Hato Moa
My Review:
Don't read this until you've finished Holiday Star; there are spoilers in here.

Comic-wise - it's a short little ditty meant for fans, but with a little bit of an Inio Asano-like bent in its storytelling.

Title: The Fade Out
Author: Ed Brubaker
My Review:
A fleshed-out work with incredible style in art, story, and colour. The colour is beyond amazing!

The noir genre is a special kind of conceit that can often lead to excessive and bawdry characterization; much of the story here tends to get away from being plain old miserable, but it does prop up from time to time. (Consider a lot of the women in this comic - they end up subservient to male desire. It's a result of the time period, but one can't help recall the likes of Fritz Lang's The Big Heat when reading into these interactions.)

The only real comment I'd have to give to justify a 4-star rating is that the pacing does kind of wobble in places (I'm thinking particularly of the endgame pacing, and of the sudden "aha" revelations that occur just a bit too often). The ending is a little bit of a brick joke, too, but the last few pages don't really mar the final product all too badly.

Title: Goodnight Punpun Omnibus, Vol. 5
Author: Inio Asano
My Review: Transitory stuff. Some important meetings happen, and things spiral further out of control, but the indelible images of previous instalments make this volume seem pale in comparison.

Title: Tekkon Kinkreet: Black and White
Author: Taiyo Matsumoto
Additional Authors: Lillian Olsen, R. Suter, Elisabeth Kawasaki

Title: Neo Parasyte f
Author: Hitoshi Iwaaki
Additional Authors: Asumiko Nakamura, Ema Tōyama, Kaori Yuki, Renjuro Kindaichi, Banko Kuze
My Review:
As with any anthology championing a specific franchise or work, you're bound to have dips in quality and stories - what's surprising about this one is that, for all of the reverence by each artist, the resulting stories are actually quite engaging. The standalone ones I find typically work the best, though not always.

The biggest strength of this anthology, I find, is the organization of each one - it ends, suitably, on a moment of reflection - one that can easily be channelled into the work's themes and its reception since being finished.

Title: iZombie Omnibus
Author: Chris Roberson
My Review:
Clearly a ton more ambition in the premise and overall execution than was otherwise anticipated (shame on me), but I do think that the plot is overly convoluted to the point of exposing its artifice. The different art styles don't really help the matter, and aside from the (very nice) afterword explaining the genesis of the idea, we as readers don't really get much in the way of "outline-to-product."

I'm not really a fan of how some artists render their anatomy, either; frequently in the midpoint of the book, some characters look as though they've been sketched out without regard for muscle tone in arms and legs, so their "arms" tend to look more like limp noodles. Hey, it happens - but this isn't an anthology, and it would have been nice to kind of get an explanation in-book as to why.

The story itself teeters toward fluff and mock-epic - I wouldn't be surprised if Neil Gaiman was a frequent inspiration for some of the later plot points. Ultimately, though, I do think that iZOMBIE got carried away with so many supernatural elements added into the mix, and the TV series (as weird as this is to say) actually made the right decision in moving away from the original material, to focus specifically on the zombie angle.

Both are worth checking out, in the end; I'm not quite as enamoured with the comic series as I was with the first season of the TV show, to be honest, but they both have different goals in mind. Interestingly enough, their biggest strengths, despite being so strongly different in plot and themes, are also the same - there's just a lot of good old raunchy humour.

Title: Beast and Man: The Roots of Human Nature
Author: Mary Midgley

Title: Trilogy
Author: Jon Fosse
My Review:
An extremely weary telling of legacies and generations, leaning backwards in exhaustion and in reflection. Fosse's writing here is much more pronounced and effective, I think, and his aptitude for the flow of words that scream consciousness fits well with themes of travel and liquid.

This is a collection that is enriched by being part of a whole; separately, the first is probably the better of the three entries by way of not carrying any burdens as an instalment, and in terms of form the third has more potent richness in reflection - one of the key elements that made Morning and Evening's culmination memorable. Together, though, the instalments begin to build upon a mythos that doesn't quite escape the fabric of dreams - or legacies that run continually into disparate elements of each other.

Rich in purple ambiguity as it is, Trilogy packs a lot of detail and environment in its writing, and the total sum is something not to be ignored or tossed aside.

Title: Morning and Evening
Author: Jon Fosse
My Review:
The ending is, strangely enough, affecting in a way that solemnity often is, but so much of the power behind Fosse's writing is paradoxically the flaw that can make it a tedious chore to read.

Some of my grievances with this book revolve around the pace - the language is often beautiful, if obscure in demonstrating relations, location, specifics (as I am sure was intentional), but the pacing is a little too hurried.

The sum total of the events that occur don't really add up to anything momentous or even ruminative in its mundanity, and while there is more toiled introspection in the latter half, it never works as complement to the first half. One may argue that there's a point to this, but I don't really see it.

Title: 'Art'
Author: Yasmina Reza
My Review:
"In fact I can no longer bear any kind of rational argument, nothing formative in the world, nothing great or beautiful in the world has ever been born of rational argument."

I had the pleasure of watching a production of this play in Montreal, with Marc changed from male to female. As any good idea, the casting helped diversify and expand upon the work; too often Marc and Serge as characters riposte upon one another with the same voice.

The play itself is, I imagine, translated well - I don't have access to the original French, and I suspect a lot would be lost on me. What does come off, in this translation, is a very moving tribute to the nature of contemporary art, and Yasmina Reza really does let her characters rip into it every chance she gets. The only qualm is that, for all of the build-up, the ending does deflate a little. It's a good ending on paper, and thematically so, but the asides to the audience throughout and leading to the "epilogue" don't particularly serve as good pay-off for an incredible rest of the work.

To be fair, this is a rather spectacular and remarkable work, and it deserves merit for equally standing on its own and shining in the hands of others. Read it as you would, but watching it is quite preferable.

Title: Adulthood Is a Myth (Sarah's Scribbles, #1)
Author: Sarah Andersen
My Review:
It's a collection of strips that I'm only familiar with from Facebook and the internet, but it came in with a bunch of other books I've ordered for the family.

Being the creep I am, I palmed through it. It's delightful as a small collection of thoughts, but I can't help but feel that these strips worked better as stand-alone; they do have structure compiled together, as they are, it's more that you get to see almost the same idea repeated verbatim throughout.

Then again, this isn't really the kind of material for me anyhow. If you like her work absolutely get this; it's good unwinding material. Four stars for the work put in.

Title: Einstein's Gift
Author: Vern Thiessen
My Review:
If it is a little too on-the-nose, then I suspect that is because we have not yet outgrown the concerns that plague this work. It's still as vivid and as extraordinary as the first time I read it, though it does reek of a little theatricality.

But beyond all else it is eminently readable, both as script and as theatre, and I do still think of it as highly communicative of its intent. Hence, the five stars.

Title: Stone Butch Blues
Author: Leslie Feinberg
My Review:
I don't think I can really say much about my opinions re: the book, because truthfully the voice of Jess - as Leslie Feinberg herself had stated in her author's notes - is the only one who can fully articulate how great the ideas behind this work is. I'll try to champion the work's rating in terms of fiction, because as a medium for the championing of the ignored and abused there can be no dispute.

There are moments where the language employed - written closer to moral haranguing than description - almost works against the experiences described here; I'd say the first few chapters are the biggest examples here. But by and large, you're enveloped into a writer whose talents successfully marry message and characters into a work that is legible and affecting. I do believe that the ending is perhaps a little too hopeful for what has prefaced it, but then again it does come as hard-won all the same.

Title: American Gods (American Gods #1)
Author: Neil Gaiman
My Review: A pinnacle of exemplary writing in the fascinating canon of Gaiman's oeuvre.

Title: The Heart of a Dog
Author: Mikhail Bulgakov
My Review: A surreal masterpiece of fiction that bleeds all too contemporary.

Title: When Five Years Pass
Author: Federico García Lorca
My Review:
I think my understanding of this play soured from first watching a student production of it, before reading the text. It's also possible that, had I any knowledge of any cultural underpinnings that Garcia Lorca invokes here, my appreciation would be much higher than it is.

The fact remains that this play is nigh impenetrable, and works better as obscurist surrealism than anything that should be performed.

To be sure, there are moments of unwavering beauty in this text, and the best images evoked (the sea in a glass, anyone?) inhabit their own spaces. But beauty without substance turns brittle and self-mocking; then, with enough reading, it withers and prunes to rotten fluid.

Come to this as a devout fan of Lorca, and don't make this your introduction. It will only turn you away.

Title: Chicago: City on the Make
Author: Nelson Algren
Additional Authors: Studs Terkel, David Schmittgens, Bill Savage
My Review:
Not really sure what I can say in offering, other than that this is a natural work of fiction that enterprises a city now defunct in its depiction. It's a good place, perhaps, to start with Algren; or, The Man With the Golden Arm; or, Never Come Morning. The point is he's a writer to read, and to think about, beyond the Sinatra and Preminger adaptation of TMWTGA.

It's going to take a while to digest this one, even with - or because of - the paucity of this volume.

Title: Transcending Space: Architectural Places in Works by Henry David Thoreau, E.E. Cummings, and John Barth
Author: Taimi Anne Olsen

Title: Dancing at the Edge of the World: Thoughts on Words, Women, Places
Author: Ursula K. Le Guin
My Review:
Five stars for her Talks and Essays; three for her Reviews. It's not that her reviews are terrible per sé, but they are by nature fragmented and removed of their original context.

LeGuin is more engaging, I believe, when she is given free reign and time to espouse her ideas and comments. Reviews impose limitations through word count, and subsequently justification; it doesn't quite help that in this collection some reviews too are more paragraphs of different works assembled together, without division to better indicate a change in topic. If the reviews held any connective tissue, they weren't readily apparent to me.

Title: Selections From Strange Tales From the Liaozhai Studio: Volume 1
Author: Pu Songling
My Review:
This rating applies to the first of four books in a set. A total rating, I hope, will come soon after the fourth is finished.

Collections like these are a bit hard to review, purely because in the end you're either juggling an act of comprehensivity, or curating a selection that you think would appeal to the reader. This set, I believe, aims for the former; the weakness of doing so for Strange Tales from the Liaozhai Studio (of which, the preface discloses, there are around 488 stories - perhaps even more, if one wishes to include variances in scholarship) is that so many of the stories repeat themselves.

While these stories make for great entertainment - indeed there have been several filmed versions, such as the Painted Skin films - they are also meant to be digested rather in selections. When one cobbles together all the transcribed works of Pu Songling, the sum total is a dizzying and frankly obtuse tome that irritates in how much it repeats itself.

The translations, I am told, are rather terrible - but then again my source is someone who doesn't have a background in translation anyways, and aside from that the preface is worth reading for those interested in the subject. It won't dispense of any scholarly knowledge, but - for one unacquainted with these works - I believe it is a good overview of why this collection exists, and furthermore why it is rightly included in the pantheon of classic Chinese literature.

Title: Brighter Day: A Jellyfish Story
Author: Craig Dorfman
My Review:
Let's be real: if you've heard the band Jellyfish and liked what they have to offer, you're probably aware of this book already. They're a fantastic band, and the book is absolutely worth getting if you're a die-hard fan.

This rating is more for the casual listener who might have stumbled upon this book by pure chance (although I would be heavily surprised, to be quite frank, if one does) - it's a little too colored, in my opinion, by pure idolatry for its cast, and lots of the recollections come off as pure "fan fiction" with imagined dialogues and sitcom-esque scenarios. Perhaps a more steady editing process, or a more detached style, would have come across as a bit more natural and less hysterical. But, then, with a more detached perspective, one would probably lose a lot of interesting tidbits, and the tidbits are really what make this book interesting.

I'm not a big fan of speculation in journalism, so I suspect that is why I've been so cool towards this publication - but, rest assured, I do recommend it for those interested in the band. I just can't see myself recommending it for others.

Title: The Hawryliw Process: Part Two
Author: Robert  Allen
My Review:
Not so enamoured with this final product as I was with the first, and I suspect here is a burning out - a kind of conglomeration of ideas over content. Nonetheless, it does gallop to a very neat little sleight-of-hand (if not tedious, in which case take off a star or two).

I'm not really so keen on fiction unfolding into meta-fiction and then dissipating, since so often the conceit by making itself bare ceases to interest the reader. I think this is true of The Hawryliw Process, unfortunately - but as a "Process," I can't fault it for that. I just simply can't recommend it wholeheartedly.

Title: The Hawryliw Process: Part One
Author: Robert  Allen
My Review:
So far this book is either 3 stars, for muddling plot contrivances and a desire to meta-narrate that induces suffrage in the reader, or 5 stars, for the overwhelming clarity of vision and beauty in the ugly dictum of his writing. I'm not entirely sure where I'm headed yet, and Book Two is just around the corner, so 4 stars it is until I can sort my thoughts together.

How funny that this book should appear for me, in the midst of my own clamour and disjointed thought discrepancies?

(Even more scary: why haven't people reviewed this here? It's a genuinely good book!)

Title: Beijing Comrades
Author: Beijing Tongzhi
Additional Authors: Bei Tong, Scott E. Myers, Petrus Liu
My Review:
As a historical document in the realm of the cyber-novel, it's an important event - and a huge milestone in getting to understand a culture so thoroughly dominated by the cultural ethos.

As a novel, though, you've likely read this plot - and several incarnations therein, spread throughout (whether in Brokeback Mountain or Blue is the Warmest Color) - before. Its strength, then, comes from the events that transpire to reach this conclusion; it meanders sometimes, and truthfully, it's a text that has transfigured itself several times, to the point where I don't really know how much of this is the "original" text that so successfully captured China.

It's absolutely worth reading, in any case.

My Review:
The kind of book that meanders a bit, expresses itself naïvely and with simple elocution, and is totally, completely honest in delivery. It's optimistic, and it reflects its timeliness, but its greatest strength is that at its best moments, the minute observations of Warhol can hint at a nice, universal truth.

Isn't that what we want to read, anyways?

Title: Gyo
Author: Junji Ito
My Review:
The main tale, Gyo, is probably worth about 3 stars - hampered seriously by characters without characterization, and plodded by ideas almost thrown haphazardly. What redeems it somewhat is the always effective art, and the striking originality it first conveys, before it inevitably succumbs to explanation.

The bonus works include The Enigma of Amigara Fault (a classic, precisely because it never seeks to explain its conceit of horror nor overstay its welcome with efforts to reclaim its original macabre elements), and The Sad Tale of the Principal Post, which is thoroughly unremarkable.

Title: A Short History of Decay
Author: Emil M. Cioran
My Review: An explosion of negation that murks its way through the reader's mind, I would like to say. There's a lot of bile for mankind thrown about, for sure, but Cioran's writing is never less than enthusiastic about the self-flagellation he gives to himself, and by extension the world.

you'll love this book or you'll hate it.

obviously you know which camp I'm in, but I will argue it's never boring (hence 2 stars instead of 1).

Title: Stories of Your Life and Others
Author: Ted Chiang
My Review:
The individual content can easily merit five stars, depending on the story; also considering that these ideas expressed here have found function in so many other stories, and that these stories span from the early '90s to 2002, their value in shaping speculative fiction is undeniable.

The reason for the four stars is really because I think the stories are somewhat lessened by being grouped in this way, despite their evolution in chronological and ideological terms. Ursula K. LeGuin's two-part anthology, The Unreal and the Real, didn't seek to bridge all stories through chronology or by generic categorization (Application / Language / Perception), but by applying care in selecting how her stories would be read. Here, in contrast, many of the "whammy" moments that often tend to clarify speculative fiction (and, let's face it, short stories belonging to "general fiction," whatever that may be) are somewhat lessened by a lack of separation.

This last part is really a subjective tenet of mine, however, so take from it as you will. This is a great collection, my complaints notwithstanding, and deserves reading - and thinking, and reading, and thinking again long after your eyes have left the last ink blot on the last page.

Title: Picnic at Hanging Rock
Author: Joan Lindsay
My Review:
A very lyrical tale with great, haunting undertones. The biggest thing that works against its rich prose (and you won't forget "dark against the paling sky" anytime soon) is unfortunately its obstinate stance in encouraging focus on the mystery. Some tales that emerge from the "central mystery" are oftentimes more compelling, and I think that is often the case with this work - although, you would be right in arguing that much of the actions and consequences are in direct relation.

This will pair well with Songs for the Missing, by Stewart O'Nan.

Title: Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows (Harry Potter, #7)
Author: J.K. Rowling
My Review:
Ending with a critical bang, the last of the Harry Potter canon (not including the miscellaneous spin-offs or viscera perpetuated by one "Hermione Grainger") serves to once again reach the heights of the fourth book, while also serving as a delight for reading by both children and adults. The only real complaint is the occasional all-caps routine of shouting (which reads as complete fan fiction and a style of an immature writer), and the deplorable epilogue, which attempts to wrap up nicely the futures of everyone involved.

There is a certain engagement with the imagination, where an open ending can leave one satisfied with how they might imagine the future of these beloved characters. In any case, it wouldn't lead to such admissions as "HarryxHermione" or "Ron's a tramp."

Title: The Dialectics of Seeing: Walter Benjamin and the Arcades Project
Author: Susan Buck-Morss

Title: Comments on the Society of the Spectacle
Author: Guy Debord

Title: Chinese Rhyme-Prose
Author: Burton Watson
My Review:
I put this off for far too long, since my initial thoughts were to finish this in spurts (and thus digest the material), and to finish off some other books I had on a reading list for quite some time.

The translations are simple, as the foreword attests, and will disappoint if you are looking for a scholarly list with perfunctory liner notes. The latter does exist to some extent, but much more emphasis is rightly accrued to the translations themselves, which can be enjoyed purely as world-building (in the way J.R.R. Tolkien at his best could do), as well as a great introduction towards the spellbinding cast Asian prose can exact.

Title: Harry Potter and the Cursed Child: Parts One and Two (Harry Potter, #8)
Author: John Tiffany
My Review:
There was bound to be backlash, and there was.
When following up with a commercially-acclaimed series that has reached its zenith, you're bound to be asked whether the latest entry is necessary - or even wanted. Unfortunately, this play fails on both counts, though if it was divorced from its origins (as a Harry Potter work) I have no doubt it would be received with a more lukewarm response.

It's not terrible, but it's kind of boring in its approach. I'm told that the staged work is a more effective sight to behold, and I think I can agree with that. The Harry Potter series has the rare distinction of being both influenced by its filmic counterpart, and vice versa - so to really rate this based on the written word alone is ridiculous.

I guess I'll wear that distinction, then.

Author: David Tibet

James, Vernon Lee, L.A. Lewis, Thomas Ligotti, Arthur Machen, Guy de Maupassant, Charles Perrault, Thomas De Quincey, Saki, Count Stenbock, Montague Summers, H. Russell Wakefield, Edith Wharton, Ania Goszczyńska
My Review:
A great collection of tales - though, because of the anthological status and the relative availability of these stories in the wild, you're most likely going to purchase this based on the stature and credibility of one David Tibet. All of these works hold merit, and all have astounding riches to bestow upon the reader; however, their organization here seem a little more haphazard than perhaps I would have liked.
The limited edition includes a svelte little copy of The Grimoire, and considering the more fatalistic outcomes of this collection, it's easy to see why this work was ultimately not included as part of the fabric of The Moons at Your Door.

Title: The Exploding Boy and Other Tiny Tales
Author: Nick Parker
My Review:
A fascinating set of stories, aptly chiselled down into micro-organisms of a successful marriage between style and substance. The strength of these stories boil down towards their rather timeless nature, which, alongside the Bathelme-ian demonstration of dry wit and endless creativity, make this an easy and engaging read.
Not all stories are as successful, to my eyes (some stories seem too apt to tell similar odes of self-destruction and world-wearying nausea), but this collection merits closer reading, and should be a classic given time and stature.

Title: Forbidden Fruit: From the Letters of Abelard and Heloise (Great Loves, #2)
Author: Pierre Abélard
Additional Authors: Abbess of the Paraclete Heloise, Betty Radice, M.T. Clanchy

Title: Hard-Boiled Wonderland and the End of the World
Author: Haruki Murakami

Title: The Grimoire
Author: Montague Summers
My Review: It's a tale of average proportions, as the other reviewer correctly stated, and comes as a bonus for having ordered the hardcover edition of The Moons at Your Door. Having said that, though, it's a beautiful edition - and addition - to the library that demonstrates David Tibet's own cultivated interests in the arcane.

Title: Night on the Galactic Railroad & Other Stories from Ihatov
Author: Kenji Miyazawa
My Review: Rather a glimpse of Miyazawa's interests than a cohesive and fleshed-out argument of a collection, the highlight story is the titular Night on the Galactic Railroad. The other stories, while interesting in their own right, never quite reach the same level of transcendence nor the heartfelt importance - something which may also have come about due to the rather limpid writing, which may either be a result of translation-gone-awry in the search for comprehension, or Miyazawa's own ideas overwhelming his rather simple style.

Title: Japanoise: Music at the Edge of Circulation (Sign, Storage, Transmission)
Author: David C. Novak

Title: The Vegetarian
Author: Han Kang
My Review: The language is not all that stunning, but the clear ideas presented and the minimal approach to conveying the characters all around make this a fascinating read. I can't help but think of certain surrealistic tendencies that this book shares with the likes of Hong Sang-soo and Lee Chang-dong's theatrical works, however, which may point towards a cultural landscape. My knowledge on Korean fiction is limited, though.

My Review: Great work relating both autobiographical influences and film subversion. Recommended as supplementary reading to Immoral Tales and Film as a Subversive Art.

Author: Marie Chaix
My Review: A compilation of thoughts, conveyances and idolatry that never quite matches the intimate nuances or sincerely anguished love of her earlier work, Silences, or a Woman's Life.

Author: Qiu Miaojin
My Review: Experimental structure and narrative that, like the I Ching and Cortazar's Hopscotch, play around with time, narrator-narrative, and ultimately emotive suffering - achieving a sort of universal epitome of human suffering and sublimation.

Title: The Dead
Author: James Joyce
My Review: One of the rare stories that works both as a standalone process, and as a culmination of that singular dread Joyce found himself in with Dublin.

Title: Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (Harry Potter, #5)
Author: J.K. Rowling
My Review: Narratively weaker than its predecessor, and now with the full-time bloat of an author trying to edge in darker waters, Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix doesn't quite have the verve or the stakes that earlier books did - but then again, it no longer functions as a standalone narrative with a reoccurring villain either.

Title: Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (Harry Potter, #4)
Author: J.K. Rowling
My Review: Engaging and disquieting, this installment perfectly captures the highs and lows of the whole Harry Potter canon - the meek conciseness of the earlier works have now been replaced by a sure hand, and an engagement with the material that will close this heptalogy strongly.

Title: Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (Harry Potter, #3)
Author: J.K. Rowling
My Review: Beginning with this installment of the franchise, the series begins to take a darker and more serious tone, which would culminate with the fourth book.

Title: Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone (Harry Potter, #1)
Author: J.K. Rowling
My Review: Auspicious start towards a childrens' series. It hints at becoming the next Magic Treehouse, rather than the ultimate sensation / His Dark Materials-esque work that it is today.

Title: Reel Asian: Asian Canada on Screen
Author: Elaine Chang
My Review: Interesting work that illuminates a spectrum of issues related towards the idea of Asian/Canadian (Asian Canadian), as opposed to the significant other "Asian-Canadian". It doesn't quite give an introduction to Asian Canadian cinema, which was what I was hoping for, but that doesn't seem to be its goal; rather, it aims to create awareness of that developing culture independent of one's cultural origins, yet indebted towards their traditions.

Title: The Luminaries
Author: Eleanor Catton
My Review: Beautifully written book that unfortunately meanders in the beginning, and resolves in a rather arcane manner. The prose leading to the end, as well as the machinations, are clever but ultimately feel hollow.

It was a good deal.
